# PostgreSQL 17 Installation Guide on CentOS

### (Same for RHEL/AlmaLinux/Rocky Linux)

This guide provides a streamlined process for installing **PostgreSQL 17** on RHEL-based distributions. Follow these steps to set up the repository, install the server, and initialize your database environment.

---

## 1. Repository Setup

The first step is to install the official PostgreSQL Yum Repository and disable the default built-in PostgreSQL module to avoid version conflicts.

Bash

```shell
# Install the PostgreSQL repository RPM
sudo dnf install -y https://download.postgresql.org/pub/repos/yum/reporpms/EL-$(rpm -E %{rhel})-x86_64/pgdg-redhat-repo-latest.noarch.rpm

# Disable the built-in PostgreSQL module
sudo dnf -qy module disable postgresql
```

## 2. Install PostgreSQL 17 Server

Once the repository is configured, you can install the specific PostgreSQL 17 packages.

Bash

```shell
# Install the PostgreSQL 17 server package
sudo dnf install -y postgresql17-server
```

---

## 3. Database Initialization

Before starting the service, you must initialize the database storage area (the cluster).

Bash

```shell
# Initialize the database cluster
sudo /usr/pgsql-17/bin/postgresql-17-setup initdb
```

## 4. Service Management

Enable the service so it starts automatically on boot, and then start the service immediately.

Bash

```shell
# Enable automatic start on boot
sudo systemctl enable postgresql-17

# Start the PostgreSQL service
sudo systemctl start postgresql-17
```

---

## 5. Verify Installation

To ensure the installation was successful and the service is active, check the system status.

Bash

```shell
# Check the running status
systemctl status postgresql-17
```

